1
00:01:44,771 --> 00:01:48,006
On Sunday, August 12, 1961...

2
00:01:48,007 --> 00:01:50,776
the eyes of America
were on the nation's capital...

3
00:01:50,777 --> 00:01:54,447
where Roger Maris was hitting
home runs number 44 and 45...

4
00:01:54,448 --> 00:01:55,948
against the Senators.

5
00:01:55,949 --> 00:01:58,117
On that same day,
without any warning...

6
00:01:58,118 --> 00:02:00,453
the East German Communists
sealed off the border...

7
00:02:00,454 --> 00:02:03,256
between East and West Berlin.

8
00:02:03,257 --> 00:02:04,490
I only mention this...

9
00:02:04,491 --> 00:02:06,726
to show the kind of people
we're dealing with...

10
00:02:06,727 --> 00:02:08,994
real shifty.

11
00:02:08,995 --> 00:02:11,564
Having been stationed in Berlin
and having dealt with them...

12
00:02:11,565 --> 00:02:13,054
I know what I'm talking about.

13
00:02:13,933 --> 00:02:15,834
Let's go back to last June.

14
00:02:15,835 --> 00:02:18,705
Considering the abnormal
situation of a divided city...

15
00:02:18,706 --> 00:02:21,106
life in Berlin
was more or less normal.

16
00:02:21,107 --> 00:02:23,409
Traffic flowed freely
through the Brandenburg Gate...

17
00:02:23,410 --> 00:02:24,944
and it wasn't really
too much trouble...

18
00:02:24,945 --> 00:02:26,479
to pass from one side
of the Iron Curtain...

19
00:02:26,480 --> 00:02:27,779
to the other.

20
00:02:27,780 --> 00:02:30,683
Some of the East German police
were rude and suspicious.

21
00:02:30,684 --> 00:02:33,051
Others were suspicious and rude.

22
00:02:33,052 --> 00:02:35,622
The eastern sector,
under Communist domination...

23
00:02:35,623 --> 00:02:37,156
was still in rubble...

24
00:02:37,157 --> 00:02:39,592
but the people went about
their daily business...

25
00:02:39,593 --> 00:02:40,752
parading.

26
00:03:33,179 --> 00:03:34,846
These constant provocations...

27
00:03:34,847 --> 00:03:37,183
failed to provoke
the West Berliners.

28
00:03:37,184 --> 00:03:38,741
They were too busy rebuilding.

29
00:03:39,953 --> 00:03:42,655
The western sector,
under Allied protection...

30
00:03:42,656 --> 00:03:44,623
was peaceful, prosperous...

31
00:03:44,624 --> 00:03:47,320
and enjoyed all the blessings
of democracy.

32
00:03:51,698 --> 00:03:53,098
Just by coincidence...

33
00:03:53,099 --> 00:03:55,329
this happens to be
the company I work for.

34
00:04:12,585 --> 00:04:13,916
Danke schön.

35
00:04:21,928 --> 00:04:23,122
Danke schön, Fritz.

36
00:04:30,637 --> 00:04:32,195
Danke schön.

37
00:04:44,384 --> 00:04:46,682
Danke schön already.

38
00:04:55,328 --> 00:04:56,761
Sitzen machen.

39
00:05:06,272 --> 00:05:08,035
Schlemmer!

40
00:05:12,178 --> 00:05:13,702
Good morning, Mr. MacNamara.

41
00:05:14,847 --> 00:05:16,515
Schlemmer, how many times
have I told you...

42
00:05:16,516 --> 00:05:17,984
I don't want those people
standing at attention...

43
00:05:17,985 --> 00:05:20,286
every time
I come into the office.

44
00:05:20,287 --> 00:05:22,587
I know.
I've given strict orders.

45
00:05:22,588 --> 00:05:24,791
Can't they get it through
their Prussian heads?

46
00:05:24,792 --> 00:05:26,159
They're living
in a democracy now.

47
00:05:26,160 --> 00:05:27,526
That is the trouble.

48
00:05:27,527 --> 00:05:29,062
In the old days,
if I ordered them to sit...

49
00:05:29,063 --> 00:05:30,195
they would sit.

50
00:05:30,196 --> 00:05:32,031
Now with a democracy,
they do what they want.

51
00:05:32,032 --> 00:05:33,298
What they want is to stand.

52
00:05:33,299 --> 00:05:35,001
Next, any word yet
from the mayor's office?

53
00:05:35,002 --> 00:05:36,234
Yes, sir. Negative.

54
00:05:36,235 --> 00:05:37,469
They absolutely
will not permit us...

55
00:05:37,470 --> 00:05:39,272
to install a Coke machine
in the Reichstag.

56
00:05:39,273 --> 00:05:41,139
Sometimes I wonder
who won the war.

57
00:05:41,140 --> 00:05:42,375
Next, did you pick up
those airline tickets...

58
00:05:42,376 --> 00:05:43,443
for my wife and children?

59
00:05:43,444 --> 00:05:45,043
Yes, sir. Positive.

60
00:05:45,044 --> 00:05:46,713
Three seats on a 6:00 plane
to Venice.

61
00:05:46,714 --> 00:05:47,780
They change in Frankfurt.

62
00:05:47,781 --> 00:05:48,780
That reminds me.

63
00:05:48,781 --> 00:05:49,949
Call the Frankfurt plant
and have them ship us...

64
00:05:49,950 --> 00:05:51,383
another 100,000 bottles.

65
00:05:51,384 --> 00:05:53,553
People keep smuggling Cokes
into the eastern sector...

66
00:05:53,554 --> 00:05:54,554
and not returning the empties.

67
00:05:54,555 --> 00:05:55,687
Yes, sir.

68
00:05:55,688 --> 00:05:57,390
Next, I'm expecting the Russian
Trade Commission at 10:20.

69
00:05:57,391 --> 00:05:58,558
When they get here,
show them right in.

70
00:05:58,559 --> 00:05:59,558
Yes, sir.

71
00:05:59,559 --> 00:06:00,693
Next. Schlemmer, you're fired.

72
00:06:00,694 --> 00:06:01,626
Sir?

73
00:06:01,627 --> 00:06:04,029
Unless you stop clicking
your heels around here!

74
00:06:04,030 --> 00:06:06,432
Yes, sir. Oh, I'm sorry.
I keep forgetting myself.

75
00:06:06,433 --> 00:06:07,833
That old Gestapo training, huh?

76
00:06:07,834 --> 00:06:09,702
Please, Mr. MacNamara.
You mustn't say that.

77
00:06:09,703 --> 00:06:10,702
It is not true.

78
00:06:10,703 --> 00:06:13,106
Just between us, Schlemmer,
what did you do during the war?

79
00:06:13,107 --> 00:06:14,340
I was in der untergrund...

80
00:06:14,341 --> 00:06:15,341
the underground.

81
00:06:15,342 --> 00:06:16,341
Resistance fighter?

82
00:06:16,342 --> 00:06:17,710
No. Motorman.
In the underground.

83
00:06:17,711 --> 00:06:18,744
You know, the subway.

84
00:06:18,745 --> 00:06:20,847
Of course, you were anti-Nazi,
and you never liked Adolf.

85
00:06:20,848 --> 00:06:22,147
Adolf who?

86
00:06:22,148 --> 00:06:23,515
You see, down where I was...

87
00:06:23,516 --> 00:06:24,917
I didn't know what
was going on out there.

88
00:06:24,918 --> 00:06:26,302
Nobody ever told me
anything.

89
00:06:26,303 --> 00:06:27,687
That'll be all, Schlemmer.

90
00:06:27,688 --> 00:06:29,052
Herausmachen!

91
00:06:58,017 --> 00:06:59,317
Guten Morgen, MacNamara.

92
00:06:59,318 --> 00:07:01,320
And a guten Morgen to you,
Fräulein Ingeborg.

93
00:07:01,321 --> 00:07:02,320
It is not "frow-line."

94
00:07:02,321 --> 00:07:05,057
It is "froy-line"
with an umlaut.

95
00:07:05,058 --> 00:07:07,492
I'll say. Monthly report.

96
00:07:07,493 --> 00:07:10,062
To Wendell P. Hazeltine,
home office, Atlanta, Georgia.

97
00:07:10,063 --> 00:07:12,665
From C.R. MacNamara,
Berlin branch.

98
00:07:12,666 --> 00:07:13,900
Production figures were made.

99
00:07:13,901 --> 00:07:15,967
270,000 cases.

100
00:07:15,968 --> 00:07:19,305
Consumption per capita
now 5.2% above last year.

101
00:07:19,306 --> 00:07:21,457
Outselling Rhine wine
eight to one.

102
00:07:21,458 --> 00:07:23,609
Rapidly creeping up
on draft beer.

103
00:07:23,610 --> 00:07:25,510
Next, publicity campaign...

104
00:07:25,511 --> 00:07:28,514
to reorient German
businessmen's lunch succeeding.

105
00:07:28,515 --> 00:07:31,684
27% now having Coke
with their knackwurst.

106
00:07:31,685 --> 00:07:34,085
Now, here's a real hot flash.

107
00:07:34,086 --> 00:07:36,456
We may become
the first American company...

108
00:07:36,457 --> 00:07:38,190
to crack the Iron Curtain.

109
00:07:38,191 --> 00:07:40,293
I have started
preliminary negotiations...

110
00:07:40,294 --> 00:07:41,860
with a Russian representative.

111
00:07:41,861 --> 00:07:44,230
It looks most promising.
More later.

112
00:07:44,231 --> 00:07:45,219
Next...

113
00:07:46,132 --> 00:07:47,766
what did you do
over the weekend?

114
00:07:47,767 --> 00:07:49,669
Nothing.
I stayed home waiting for you.

115
00:07:49,670 --> 00:07:50,920
I tried to make it, believe me.

116
00:07:50,921 --> 00:07:52,897
I just couldn't get away...

117
00:07:52,898 --> 00:07:54,874
but there's good news tonight.

118
00:07:54,875 --> 00:07:57,343
Yes? Mrs. MacNamara?

119
00:07:57,344 --> 00:07:58,503
Put her on.

120
00:07:59,645 --> 00:08:01,713
Yes, Phyllis.
What's the matter?

121
00:08:01,714 --> 00:08:03,916
It's Tommy. We're having
a little crisis here.

122
00:08:03,917 --> 00:08:05,817
Why don't you talk to him?

123
00:08:05,818 --> 00:08:07,877
Tommy, your father's
on the phone.

124
00:08:09,555 --> 00:08:11,656
Hello, Dad. Nothing.

125
00:08:11,657 --> 00:08:13,526
It's just that Mother's
ganging up on me.

126
00:08:13,527 --> 00:08:15,193
What do you mean by that?

127
00:08:15,194 --> 00:08:17,063
I think your mother's
absolutely right.

128
00:08:17,064 --> 00:08:18,330
It's silly to pack them.

129
00:08:18,331 --> 00:08:19,732
What are you going to do
with roller skates in Venice?

130
00:08:19,733 --> 00:08:20,932
All the streets are underwater.

131
00:08:20,933 --> 00:08:24,937
So what? I'm taking my aqualung
and my snorkel.

132
00:08:24,938 --> 00:08:27,770
Here. Your husband
wants to talk to you.

133
00:08:31,477 --> 00:08:32,544
Yes, Mac?

134
00:08:32,545 --> 00:08:35,031
Look, Phyllis.
Let him pack what he wants.

135
00:08:35,032 --> 00:08:37,516
All right. I'm spoiling him.
Big deal.

136
00:08:37,517 --> 00:08:39,018
don't worry.
The car will be there at 5:00.

137
00:08:39,019 --> 00:08:40,520
Then you'll pick me up
at the office...

138
00:08:40,521 --> 00:08:41,721
and I'll take you
to the airport.

139
00:08:41,722 --> 00:08:43,321
Yes, mein führer.

140
00:08:43,322 --> 00:08:44,457
Bertha wants to know
what you'd like...

141
00:08:44,458 --> 00:08:45,675
to have for dinner tonight.

142
00:08:45,676 --> 00:08:46,835
Oh, tell her not to bother.

143
00:08:46,836 --> 00:08:47,993
I've got a desk full of work.

144
00:08:47,994 --> 00:08:49,662
I'll just grab
a quick bite somewhere.

145
00:08:49,663 --> 00:08:50,651
So long, dear.

146
00:08:51,364 --> 00:08:53,198
Like I said, good news.

147
00:08:53,199 --> 00:08:54,700
Your wife. She's making a trip?

148
00:08:54,701 --> 00:08:55,834
Is she ever.

149
00:08:55,835 --> 00:08:57,436
Going on vacation
mit die Kinder.

150
00:08:57,437 --> 00:08:58,470
Ach so.

151
00:08:58,471 --> 00:08:59,905
So tonight,
we'll split a schnitzel...

152
00:08:59,906 --> 00:09:01,524
and start
on the German lessons again.

153
00:09:01,525 --> 00:09:03,141
We should.
You must be getting rusty.

154
00:09:03,142 --> 00:09:05,244
We'll just have to work at it
twice as hard from now on.

155
00:09:05,245 --> 00:09:06,245
Das ist gut?

156
00:09:06,246 --> 00:09:07,245
Sehr gut.

157
00:09:07,246 --> 00:09:10,149
And the first thing we're gonna
do is brush up on the umlaut.

158
00:09:10,150 --> 00:09:11,446
Das ist wunderbar.

159
00:09:13,920 --> 00:09:17,287
Like all the lilacs
in Lower Bavaria.

160
00:09:19,058 --> 00:09:21,060
The Communist gentlemen
are here.

161
00:09:21,061 --> 00:09:22,060
Send them in.

162
00:09:22,061 --> 00:09:23,596
That'll be all,
Fräulein Ingeborg.

163
00:09:23,597 --> 00:09:25,131
Put that on the teletype
to Atlanta.

164
00:09:25,132 --> 00:09:26,164
Jawohl.

165
00:09:26,165 --> 00:09:27,333
And take your gum.

166
00:09:27,334 --> 00:09:28,357
Jawohl.

167
00:09:35,341 --> 00:09:36,809
Nice to see you again,
Comrade Mishkin.

168
00:09:36,810 --> 00:09:38,043
Hey, Mishkin.

169
00:09:38,044 --> 00:09:39,878
Ah, Mr. MacNamara...

170
00:09:39,879 --> 00:09:42,248
I would like to present
Commissar Peripetchikoff...

171
00:09:42,249 --> 00:09:43,883
Chairman of our
Trade Commission...

172
00:09:43,884 --> 00:09:44,950
and Comrade Borodenko...

173
00:09:44,951 --> 00:09:47,286
from the Soft Drinks
Secretariat.

174
00:09:47,287 --> 00:09:49,154
Sit down.

175
00:09:49,155 --> 00:09:50,288
Sit down, boys.

176
00:09:50,289 --> 00:09:51,757
We have no objection.

177
00:09:51,758 --> 00:09:53,224
Cigarettes? Cigars?

178
00:09:53,225 --> 00:09:54,527
Here. Take one of these.

179
00:09:54,528 --> 00:09:55,619
Thanks.

180
00:09:56,329 --> 00:09:57,329
Made in Havana.

181
00:09:57,330 --> 00:09:59,197
We have trade agreement
with Cuba.

182
00:09:59,198 --> 00:10:01,167
They send us cigars,
we send them rockets.

183
00:10:01,168 --> 00:10:02,334
Good thinking.

184
00:10:02,335 --> 00:10:03,436
Now, I understand
from Comrade Mishkin...

185
00:10:03,437 --> 00:10:04,821
that you guys are very keen...

186
00:10:04,822 --> 00:10:06,205
on getting Coca-Cola
into Russia.

187
00:10:06,206 --> 00:10:07,672
He is totally wrong.

188
00:10:07,673 --> 00:10:09,074
I did not say we are keen.

189
00:10:09,075 --> 00:10:11,344
I said we are mildly interested.

190
00:10:11,345 --> 00:10:12,538
Nevertheless...

191
00:10:14,380 --> 00:10:16,649
Comrade Mishkin suggested we
start with 6 bottling plants...

192
00:10:16,650 --> 00:10:19,447
Moscow, Leningrad,
Stalingrad, Kiev...

193
00:10:21,420 --> 00:10:23,322
You know something?
You guys got cheated.

194
00:10:23,323 --> 00:10:24,657
This is a pretty crummy cigar.

195
00:10:24,658 --> 00:10:26,157
Do not worry.

196
00:10:26,158 --> 00:10:28,592
We send them
pretty crummy rockets.

197
00:10:33,432 --> 00:10:35,534
As I was saying, six plants...

198
00:10:35,535 --> 00:10:37,470
Moscow, Leningrad, Stalingrad...

199
00:10:37,471 --> 00:10:39,405
Kiev, Kharkov, and Minsk, right?

200
00:10:39,406 --> 00:10:40,472
Totally wrong.

201
00:10:40,473 --> 00:10:41,540
I never mentioned Minsk.

202
00:10:41,541 --> 00:10:42,707
I said Pinsk.

203
00:10:42,708 --> 00:10:44,776
All right.
Pinsk is in. Minsk is out.

204
00:10:44,777 --> 00:10:47,346
Next, our contract will contain
the usual provisions.

205
00:10:47,347 --> 00:10:49,148
We supply the syrup,
you do the bottling.

206
00:10:49,149 --> 00:10:50,148
Certainly not.

207
00:10:50,149 --> 00:10:53,319
We make our own syrup.
You supply the formula.

208
00:10:53,320 --> 00:10:54,619
Forget it, gentlemen.

209
00:10:54,620 --> 00:10:55,987
That formula
stays in our vaults.

210
00:10:55,988 --> 00:10:57,423
We give it to you,
first thing we know...

211
00:10:57,424 --> 00:10:58,891
the Chinese Communists
will have it.

212
00:10:58,892 --> 00:11:01,827
No formula, no deal.

213
00:11:01,828 --> 00:11:03,428
OK. No deal.

214
00:11:03,429 --> 00:11:04,963
We do not need you.

215
00:11:04,964 --> 00:11:07,600
If we want Coca-Cola,
we invent it ourselves.

216
00:11:07,601 --> 00:11:08,600
Oh, yeah?

217
00:11:08,601 --> 00:11:10,753
In 1956, you flew
a bottle of Coke...

218
00:11:10,754 --> 00:11:12,905
to a secret
laboratory in Sverdlovsk.

219
00:11:12,906 --> 00:11:13,972
A dozen of your top chemists...

220
00:11:13,973 --> 00:11:16,609
went nuts trying to analyze
the ingredients, right?

221
00:11:16,610 --> 00:11:17,842
No comment.

222
00:11:17,843 --> 00:11:20,345
And in 1958, you planted
two undercover agents...

223
00:11:20,346 --> 00:11:22,848
in our home office in Atlanta
to steal the formula...

224
00:11:22,849 --> 00:11:24,000
and what happened?

225
00:11:24,001 --> 00:11:25,150
They both defected...

226
00:11:25,151 --> 00:11:27,153
and now they're successful
businessmen in Florida...

227
00:11:27,154 --> 00:11:29,588
packaging
instant borscht, right?

228
00:11:29,589 --> 00:11:30,922
No comment.

229
00:11:30,923 --> 00:11:32,958
Last year, you put out
a cockamamie imitation...

230
00:11:32,959 --> 00:11:34,526
Kremlin Cola.

231
00:11:34,527 --> 00:11:36,028
You tried it out in
the satellite countries...

232
00:11:36,029 --> 00:11:37,930
but even the Albanians
wouldn't drink it.

233
00:11:37,931 --> 00:11:40,599
They used it
for sheep-dip, right?

234
00:11:40,600 --> 00:11:41,900
No comment.

235
00:11:41,901 --> 00:11:44,937
So either get down to business
or get off the pot.

236
00:11:44,938 --> 00:11:46,638
My dear American friend...

237
00:11:46,639 --> 00:11:49,375
if we are to live together
in peaceful coexistence...

238
00:11:49,376 --> 00:11:51,477
there must be a certain amount
of give-and-take.

239
00:11:51,478 --> 00:11:53,111
Oh, sure.
We give, and you take.

240
00:11:53,112 --> 00:11:54,909
What is the matter?
You do not trust us?

241
00:11:55,981 --> 00:11:57,248
No comment.

242
00:11:57,249 --> 00:12:00,319
If you do not mind,
we'll have a little conference.

243
00:12:00,320 --> 00:12:01,650
Help yourself.

244
00:12:19,004 --> 00:12:20,266
What is this?

245
00:12:22,875 --> 00:12:24,375
My employees gave it to me...

246
00:12:24,376 --> 00:12:26,245
on the tenth anniversary
of the Berlin Airlift.

247
00:12:26,246 --> 00:12:28,614
Comrades,
are we going to stand here...

248
00:12:28,615 --> 00:12:30,983
and listen to this
cheap propaganda?

249
00:12:30,984 --> 00:12:32,851
Relax, Boris.

250
00:12:32,852 --> 00:12:35,321
While they're putting
Uncle Sam in cuckoo clocks...

251
00:12:35,322 --> 00:12:38,323
we will put
Soviet cosmonaut on moon.

252
00:12:38,324 --> 00:12:40,960
OK. So you guys may be the first
to shoot a man to the moon...

253
00:12:40,961 --> 00:12:42,361
but if he wants
a Coke on the way...

254
00:12:42,362 --> 00:12:44,090
you'll have to come to us.

255
00:12:52,071 --> 00:12:54,373
All right.
We agree in principle.

256
00:12:54,374 --> 00:12:55,673
You supply the syrup.

257
00:12:55,674 --> 00:12:58,210
Next, the deal will be set up
on a royalty basis.

258
00:12:58,211 --> 00:12:59,611
Royalty?

259
00:12:59,612 --> 00:13:01,397
In Russia,
we do not have royalty...

260
00:13:01,398 --> 00:13:03,181
not since we liquidate
the Czar.

261
00:13:03,182 --> 00:13:05,651
Nevertheless, you'll pay us
a percentage of the gross.

262
00:13:05,652 --> 00:13:06,818
- Money?
- Dollars.

263
00:13:06,819 --> 00:13:09,522
Instead of dollars, you would
accept three-week tour...

264
00:13:09,523 --> 00:13:10,989
of Bolshoi Ballet.

265
00:13:10,990 --> 00:13:13,025
Please. No culture, just cash.

266
00:13:13,026 --> 00:13:15,653
The ugly American.

267
00:13:16,996 --> 00:13:18,596
Next, once the plants are up...

268
00:13:18,597 --> 00:13:19,831
we reserve the right
of inspection.

269
00:13:19,832 --> 00:13:21,967
Of course, and we reserve
the right to veto.

270
00:13:21,968 --> 00:13:23,002
Our inspections will be
entitled to...

271
00:13:23,003 --> 00:13:25,838
- We veto it.
- I thought so.

272
00:13:25,839 --> 00:13:27,272
Forget details.

273
00:13:27,273 --> 00:13:28,607
You will draw up
temporary agreement...

274
00:13:28,608 --> 00:13:29,674
we will submit to Moscow.

275
00:13:29,675 --> 00:13:31,677
And I'll have to consult
with Atlanta, Georgia.

276
00:13:31,678 --> 00:13:32,977
When will papers be ready?

277
00:13:32,978 --> 00:13:34,980
I'll put my secretary
right to work on it.

278
00:13:34,981 --> 00:13:36,982
Your secretary?
She's that blond lady?

279
00:13:36,983 --> 00:13:38,415
That's the one.

280
00:13:41,220 --> 00:13:42,822
You will send papers
to East Berlin...

281
00:13:42,823 --> 00:13:44,756
with blond lady in triplicate.

282
00:13:44,757 --> 00:13:45,891
You want the papers
in triplicate...

283
00:13:45,892 --> 00:13:47,226
or the blond in triplicate?

284
00:13:47,227 --> 00:13:48,693
See what you can do.

285
00:13:48,694 --> 00:13:50,763
We are staying
at the Grand Hotel Potemkin.

286
00:13:50,764 --> 00:13:52,832
OK. Now, how about
a little vodka and Coke?

287
00:13:52,833 --> 00:13:53,965
No, thank you.

288
00:13:53,966 --> 00:13:56,836
We have emergency meeting
with Swiss trade delegation.

289
00:13:56,837 --> 00:13:59,238
They sent us
twenty carloads of cheese.

290
00:13:59,239 --> 00:14:01,640
Totally unacceptable.
Full of holes.

291
00:14:01,641 --> 00:14:02,629
Good-bye.

292
00:14:03,809 --> 00:14:05,709
See you around the campus.

293
00:14:22,061 --> 00:14:24,029
Ring a ding ding.

294
00:14:33,973 --> 00:14:35,106
What is it, Schlemmer?

295
00:14:35,107 --> 00:14:36,574
It is the overseas operator.

296
00:14:36,575 --> 00:14:39,111
You are to stand by for a call
from Atlanta, Georgia.

297
00:14:39,112 --> 00:14:41,446
Atlanta? They must
have gotten my teletype.

298
00:14:41,447 --> 00:14:43,349
I bet they're all worked up
about the Russian deal.

299
00:14:43,350 --> 00:14:44,650
- It went good?
- Good?

300
00:14:44,651 --> 00:14:46,135
Look at this, Schlemmer.

301
00:14:46,136 --> 00:14:47,619
All virgin territory...

302
00:14:47,620 --> 00:14:49,488
200 million thirsty comrades...

303
00:14:49,489 --> 00:14:51,356
Volga boatmen and Cossacks...

304
00:14:51,357 --> 00:14:53,492
Ukrainians
and Outer Mongolians...

305
00:14:53,493 --> 00:14:55,627
panting for the pause
that refreshes.

306
00:14:55,628 --> 00:14:58,130
Do you realize what it means
if I could put this across?

307
00:14:58,131 --> 00:14:59,464
Your stock, it will go up.

308
00:14:59,465 --> 00:15:01,166
I'll go up
to the number-one job...

309
00:15:01,167 --> 00:15:02,868
head of all
European operations...

310
00:15:02,869 --> 00:15:04,068
headquarters in London.

311
00:15:04,069 --> 00:15:05,704
May I be the first
to congratulate you?

312
00:15:05,705 --> 00:15:07,339
I should have had
that job five years ago.

313
00:15:07,340 --> 00:15:08,373
I was all set for it...

314
00:15:08,374 --> 00:15:10,459
even bought myself
an umbrella...

315
00:15:10,460 --> 00:15:12,544
but I got loused up
by Benny Goodman.

316
00:15:12,545 --> 00:15:13,611
Benny Goodman?

317
00:15:13,612 --> 00:15:16,381
I was in charge
of the whole Middle East...

318
00:15:16,382 --> 00:15:20,085
nine countries, fifteen bottling
plants, all facing Mecca.

319
00:15:20,086 --> 00:15:22,137
Goodman and his band
were coming through...

320
00:15:22,138 --> 00:15:24,398
on a goodwill tour
for the State Department.

321
00:15:24,399 --> 00:15:26,658
20,000 people showed up
at the concert...

322
00:15:26,659 --> 00:15:28,427
but Benny didn't
because his plane was delayed...

323
00:15:28,428 --> 00:15:30,513
by a sandstorm,
so the mob rioted...

324
00:15:30,514 --> 00:15:32,598
and marched
on the American embassy...

325
00:15:32,599 --> 00:15:34,032
so the police
turned them back...

326
00:15:34,033 --> 00:15:36,126
so they burned down
the Coca-Cola plant.

327
00:15:36,769 --> 00:15:37,769
You know it.

328
00:15:37,770 --> 00:15:39,238
There was a big rhubarb
at the home office...

329
00:15:39,239 --> 00:15:41,140
and suddenly,
I was in the doghouse...

330
00:15:41,141 --> 00:15:42,874
exiled to South America...

331
00:15:42,875 --> 00:15:44,910
schlepping that syrup
over the Andes...

332
00:15:44,911 --> 00:15:46,344
on llamas yet...

333
00:15:46,345 --> 00:15:47,713
while a bunch
of crew-cut kids...

334
00:15:47,714 --> 00:15:49,081
were being promoted
over my head!

335
00:15:49,082 --> 00:15:50,316
But you're in Berlin now.

336
00:15:50,317 --> 00:15:51,549
This is not the doghouse.

337
00:15:51,550 --> 00:15:53,318
Yeah. I used to
have nine countries.

338
00:15:53,319 --> 00:15:56,455
Now I've got half a city,
and that may blow up any day...

339
00:15:56,456 --> 00:16:00,024
but MacNamara rides again!

340
00:16:00,025 --> 00:16:01,894
I'll be
the white-haired boy now.

341
00:16:01,895 --> 00:16:03,963
I'm going all the way!

342
00:16:03,964 --> 00:16:06,030
Yes? It's Atlanta.

343
00:16:06,031 --> 00:16:08,200
Hello? Hello?
Mr. Hazeltine?

344
00:16:08,201 --> 00:16:09,600
Yes, I can hear you.

345
00:16:09,601 --> 00:16:11,436
I'm fine, Mr. Hazeltine.
How are you?

346
00:16:11,437 --> 00:16:13,238
Well, if you must know,
I'm miserable.

347
00:16:13,239 --> 00:16:15,040
Those damn magnolias
are in bloom again...

348
00:16:15,041 --> 00:16:16,975
and so is my hay fever.

349
00:16:16,976 --> 00:16:18,677
MacNamara, there's
something important...

350
00:16:18,678 --> 00:16:20,345
I'd like to discuss with you.

351
00:16:20,346 --> 00:16:22,247
I thought you would,
Mr. Hazeltine.

352
00:16:22,248 --> 00:16:23,548
You got my teletype?

353
00:16:23,549 --> 00:16:24,782
It's right here in front of me.

354
00:16:24,783 --> 00:16:26,485
Those figures from May
are not bad...

355
00:16:26,486 --> 00:16:27,536
not bad at all.

356
00:16:27,537 --> 00:16:28,586
Thank you, sir.

357
00:16:28,587 --> 00:16:30,154
And how about the Russian deal?

358
00:16:30,155 --> 00:16:32,074
Napoleon blew it,
Hitler blew it...

359
00:16:32,075 --> 00:16:34,018
but Coca-Cola's
gonna pull it off.

360
00:16:34,019 --> 00:16:35,960
Forget it, MacNamara.
Forget it.

361
00:16:35,961 --> 00:16:37,896
We are not interested
in doing business...

362
00:16:37,897 --> 00:16:39,063
behind the Iron Curtain.

363
00:16:39,064 --> 00:16:41,199
We're not interested
in the Russian market?

364
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:43,735
I wouldn't touch the Russians
with a ten-foot pole...

365
00:16:43,736 --> 00:16:45,788
and I don't want anything to do
with the Poles, either.

366
00:16:45,789 --> 00:16:47,840
But this could be the biggest
thing for the company...

367
00:16:47,841 --> 00:16:49,899
since we introduced
the six-pack!

368
00:16:51,310 --> 00:16:53,512
Well, if it's against
front-office policy...

369
00:16:53,513 --> 00:16:54,579
You're damn right...

370
00:16:54,580 --> 00:16:56,115
but that's not what
I called you about.

371
00:16:56,116 --> 00:16:57,181
Look, MacNamara.

372
00:16:57,182 --> 00:16:59,418
I'd like you to do me
a big personal favor.

373
00:16:59,419 --> 00:17:00,818
Yes, Mr. Hazeltine?

374
00:17:00,819 --> 00:17:02,021
You want me to ship
Mrs. Hazeltine...

375
00:17:02,022 --> 00:17:03,554
another set of Meissen china?

376
00:17:03,555 --> 00:17:05,657
No! It's about our daughter
Scarlett.

377
00:17:05,658 --> 00:17:07,759
She's seventeen now,
sweet girl...

378
00:17:07,760 --> 00:17:10,095
fell in love with some
damn rock'n'roll singer.

379
00:17:10,096 --> 00:17:12,130
No. That was the one before.

380
00:17:12,131 --> 00:17:14,999
This is some pimple-faced
basketball player.

381
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:17,161
Anyway, we sent her off
on a little trip to Europe.

382
00:17:18,037 --> 00:17:19,370
Where was I?

383
00:17:19,371 --> 00:17:21,840
Daughter Scarlett, pimple-faced
basketball player...

384
00:17:21,841 --> 00:17:23,042
sent her to Europe...

385
00:17:23,043 --> 00:17:24,042
Oh, yes!

386
00:17:24,043 --> 00:17:25,327
We had her spend
a couple of weeks...

387
00:17:25,328 --> 00:17:26,611
with our representative
in Rome...

388
00:17:26,612 --> 00:17:28,630
and a couple of weeks
with our man in Paris...

389
00:17:28,631 --> 00:17:31,008
and she's arriving
in Berlin this afternoon...

390
00:17:31,009 --> 00:17:32,914
so I'd appreciate it
if you and Mrs. MacNamara...

391
00:17:32,915 --> 00:17:35,035
Oh, we'd be delighted
to have her stay with us.

392
00:17:35,036 --> 00:17:37,156
It's just that
my family has made some plans...

393
00:17:37,157 --> 00:17:39,791
and I have a few plans
of my own.

394
00:17:39,792 --> 00:17:41,927
Well, if it's any sort
of imposition, never mind.

395
00:17:41,928 --> 00:17:43,561
I'm sorry I called you.

396
00:17:43,562 --> 00:17:45,964
Well, actually, I wasn't
thinking of myself.

397
00:17:45,965 --> 00:17:47,765
It's your daughter
I'm concerned about.

398
00:17:47,766 --> 00:17:50,035
With the political situation
in Berlin the way it is...

399
00:17:50,036 --> 00:17:52,004
anything can happen anytime.

400
00:17:52,005 --> 00:17:53,004
Exactly.

401
00:17:53,005 --> 00:17:55,107
That's why I want you to take
especially good care of her.

402
00:17:55,108 --> 00:17:56,607
She's just a child, really...

403
00:17:56,608 --> 00:17:58,444
and I don't like her
to stay in a hotel alone...

404
00:17:58,445 --> 00:17:59,762
at a time like this.

405
00:17:59,763 --> 00:18:01,079
She's flying Pan Am.

406
00:18:01,080 --> 00:18:03,660
The plane is due
in Berlin at 4:20...

407
00:18:03,661 --> 00:18:06,240
unless those damn Commies
shoot it down.

408
00:18:28,640 --> 00:18:30,642
Here.
You give her the flowers.

409
00:18:30,643 --> 00:18:31,810
Oh, cut it out, Phyllis!

410
00:18:31,811 --> 00:18:32,977
What was I going to do?

411
00:18:32,978 --> 00:18:34,580
The boss asked me to look
after his only daughter.

412
00:18:34,581 --> 00:18:35,847
I can't disappoint him.

413
00:18:35,848 --> 00:18:37,182
What about
your only children...

414
00:18:37,183 --> 00:18:38,316
and your only wife?

415
00:18:38,317 --> 00:18:39,651
We were all packed
and ready to go.

416
00:18:39,652 --> 00:18:40,985
don't you think
we were disappointed?

417
00:18:40,986 --> 00:18:42,987
Believe me, Phyllis,
everybody's disappointed.

418
00:18:42,988 --> 00:18:44,389
We'll just have to put things
off a couple of weeks.

419
00:18:44,390 --> 00:18:45,791
The roller skates
and the snorkel and the umlaut.

420
00:18:45,792 --> 00:18:47,158
The what?

421
00:18:47,159 --> 00:18:48,459
Right now, the important thing
is to make sure...

422
00:18:48,460 --> 00:18:50,496
that the girl has a good time
so when she goes home...

423
00:18:50,497 --> 00:18:52,764
all she'll talk about
is our man in Berlin.

424
00:18:52,765 --> 00:18:54,265
It's such a nuisance.

425
00:18:54,266 --> 00:18:56,100
Tommy will have to move
into Cindy's room.

426
00:18:56,101 --> 00:18:57,903
Bertha will have to learn
how to cook sauerbraten...

427
00:18:57,904 --> 00:18:59,103
southern style.

428
00:18:59,104 --> 00:19:00,405
Come on, Phyllis.
Make an effort.

429
00:19:00,406 --> 00:19:02,032
Yes, mein führer.

430
00:19:17,289 --> 00:19:18,524
Pardon me, is this the plane
from Paris?

431
00:19:18,525 --> 00:19:19,724
Oui, monsieur.

432
00:19:19,725 --> 00:19:21,410
Isn't there a Miss Hazeltine
among the passengers?

433
00:19:21,411 --> 00:19:23,095
There was a Miss Hazeltine
among the passengers...

434
00:19:23,096 --> 00:19:24,096
but we have lost her.

435
00:19:24,097 --> 00:19:25,096
You lost her?

436
00:19:25,097 --> 00:19:26,428
She has joined the crew.

437
00:19:34,173 --> 00:19:37,700
Scarlett Hazeltine
if I ever saw one.

438
00:19:39,545 --> 00:19:40,945
Miss Hazeltine, I'm MacNamara.

439
00:19:40,946 --> 00:19:42,548
This is Mrs. MacNamara.
Welcome to Berlin.

440
00:19:42,549 --> 00:19:43,848
Hi there!

441
00:19:43,849 --> 00:19:44,950
How was your flight?

442
00:19:44,951 --> 00:19:46,250
Just marvy.

443
00:19:46,251 --> 00:19:48,776
The boys let me
buzz Dusseldorf.

444
00:19:49,588 --> 00:19:51,000
May I have your hat?

445
00:19:51,001 --> 00:19:52,413
OK, fans. Drop them in.

446
00:19:53,959 --> 00:19:55,227
Pick one, will you, please?

447
00:19:55,228 --> 00:19:56,227
I'm game.

448
00:19:56,228 --> 00:19:57,229
What does it say?

449
00:19:57,230 --> 00:19:58,230
It says Pierre.

450
00:19:58,231 --> 00:19:59,230
That's me!

451
00:19:59,231 --> 00:20:00,298
Where do I come to pick you up?

452
00:20:00,299 --> 00:20:01,365
- What's our address?
- Why?

453
00:20:01,366 --> 00:20:03,936
Well, we just had this lottery,
and Pierre won me.

454
00:20:03,937 --> 00:20:04,936
Lucky Pierre.

455
00:20:04,937 --> 00:20:06,370
He's the navigator.

456
00:20:06,371 --> 00:20:08,139
You better
change your course, Lucky.

457
00:20:08,140 --> 00:20:10,475
You're way off the beam.
This way, Miss Hazeltine.

458
00:20:10,476 --> 00:20:11,944
Now just a darn minute.

459
00:20:11,945 --> 00:20:13,077
So long, fans!

460
00:20:13,078 --> 00:20:14,412
But that's not fair!

461
00:20:14,413 --> 00:20:17,249
Madame, I appeal to you
as a woman.

462
00:20:17,250 --> 00:20:19,218
As a matter of fact, you do.

463
00:20:19,219 --> 00:20:20,344
Au revoir.

464
00:20:21,153 --> 00:20:22,387
So you're gonna be like that?

465
00:20:22,388 --> 00:20:23,387
Like what?

466
00:20:23,388 --> 00:20:26,257
A company man like those
old poops in Rome and Paris...

467
00:20:26,258 --> 00:20:29,127
breathing down my neck
every minute, cramping my style.

468
00:20:29,128 --> 00:20:30,127
Look, Miss Hazeltine.

469
00:20:30,128 --> 00:20:31,563
You're underage,
and I'm under orders!

470
00:20:31,564 --> 00:20:33,130
Europe-what a drag!

471
00:20:33,131 --> 00:20:35,633
I've done the Colosseum bit
and the Mona Lisa bit...

472
00:20:35,634 --> 00:20:38,136
but they never take me
to any of those marvy places...

473
00:20:38,137 --> 00:20:40,972
like the Lido
and the Crazy Horse and Le Sexy.

474
00:20:40,973 --> 00:20:43,208
I promise you, you'll have
a wonderful time in Berlin.

475
00:20:43,209 --> 00:20:44,242
That's why I came.

476
00:20:44,243 --> 00:20:45,744
I hear this is
a real swinging town.

477
00:20:45,745 --> 00:20:47,211
Where did you hear that?

478
00:20:47,212 --> 00:20:48,679
don't you ever
read the headlines?

479
00:20:48,680 --> 00:20:50,382
Everybody says Berlin's
the hottest spot...

480
00:20:50,383 --> 00:20:51,916
in the world right now.

481
00:20:51,917 --> 00:20:53,318
Would you care to make
a short statement...

482
00:20:53,319 --> 00:20:54,620
for the American Forces
Network?

483
00:20:54,621 --> 00:20:55,686
Phyllis, please!

484
00:20:55,687 --> 00:20:57,489
We're a little late, folks,
so good night.

485
00:20:57,490 --> 00:20:58,522
This your ticket?

486
00:20:58,523 --> 00:20:59,957
Fritz, with the luggage machen.

487
00:20:59,958 --> 00:21:01,509
You'd better send
a cable to Tara...

488
00:21:01,510 --> 00:21:03,061
and tell them
Scarlett's checked in.

489
00:21:03,062 --> 00:21:04,829
don't bother. Let them worry.

490
00:21:04,830 --> 00:21:06,664
I didn't volunteer
for this trip.

491
00:21:06,665 --> 00:21:09,735
They deported me just to bust it
up between me and Choo Choo.

492
00:21:09,736 --> 00:21:10,819
Who's Choo Choo?

493
00:21:10,820 --> 00:21:11,902
Choo Choo Babcock.

494
00:21:11,903 --> 00:21:13,437
I met him
in a telephone booth.

495
00:21:13,438 --> 00:21:16,775
42 of us piled inside
to break the record.

496
00:21:16,776 --> 00:21:18,342
Choo Choo and I
were on the bottom.

497
00:21:18,343 --> 00:21:21,113
By the time we got out,
we were engaged.

498
00:21:21,114 --> 00:21:23,114
That's a record, all right.

499
00:21:23,115 --> 00:21:25,317
But Daddy didn't approve
because Choo Choo's folks...

500
00:21:25,318 --> 00:21:27,886
are from the wrong side
of the tracks...

501
00:21:27,887 --> 00:21:30,455
and let's face it,
my daddy's an S-N-O-B.

502
00:21:30,456 --> 00:21:31,489
A what?

503
00:21:31,490 --> 00:21:32,857
- A snob.
- Oh.

504
00:21:32,858 --> 00:21:35,093
Seventeen. Isn't that a little
young to be engaged?

505
00:21:35,094 --> 00:21:37,028
Oh, I've been
engaged four times.

506
00:21:37,029 --> 00:21:39,759
All the women in our family
are sort of hot-blooded.

507
00:21:40,899 --> 00:21:43,200
What have we got here?

508
00:21:43,201 --> 00:21:46,305
Whatever it is, it's all ours
for the next two weeks.

509
00:21:46,306 --> 00:21:47,829
Isn't that marvy?

510
00:22:11,163 --> 00:22:12,152
Schlemmer!

511
00:22:16,902 --> 00:22:19,071
I'm sorry. I will keep them
here after hours practicing.

512
00:22:19,072 --> 00:22:20,137
Never mind that.

513
00:22:20,138 --> 00:22:21,756
My chauffeur didn't
show up this morning.

514
00:22:21,757 --> 00:22:23,375
Fritz? I will find out
what happened to him.

515
00:22:23,376 --> 00:22:24,543
I don't care
what happened to him.

516
00:22:24,544 --> 00:22:25,711
Find out what happened
to my car.

517
00:22:25,712 --> 00:22:26,795
Jawohl!

518
00:22:26,796 --> 00:22:27,878
I'm sorry.

519
00:22:27,879 --> 00:22:29,626
While they are
practicing not standing...

520
00:22:29,627 --> 00:22:31,374
I will practice
not clicking my heels.

521
00:22:35,620 --> 00:22:37,489
Guten Morgen, Fräulein Ingeborg.

522
00:22:37,490 --> 00:22:38,489
Guten Morgen.

523
00:22:38,490 --> 00:22:40,826
Like freshly baked pumpernickel.

524
00:22:40,827 --> 00:22:41,859
Here's your mail.

525
00:22:41,860 --> 00:22:42,894
Here's your
"Wall Street Journal"...

526
00:22:42,895 --> 00:22:44,895
and here is my resignation.

527
00:22:44,896 --> 00:22:46,481
Resignation?
What are you talking about?

528
00:22:46,482 --> 00:22:48,275
Now you do not work me
overtime anymore.

529
00:22:48,276 --> 00:22:50,323
You do not take advantage
of me on weekends.

530
00:22:50,324 --> 00:22:52,370
You have lost all interest
in the umlaut...

531
00:22:52,371 --> 00:22:55,140
so, obviously, my services
are no longer required here.

532
00:22:55,141 --> 00:22:57,059
You know my problem.
We have this houseguest.

533
00:22:57,060 --> 00:22:58,976
You said she would
be in Berlin two weeks.

534
00:22:58,977 --> 00:23:00,746
Can I help it if she caught
the German measles?

535
00:23:00,747 --> 00:23:02,147
She's been here now two months.

536
00:23:02,148 --> 00:23:03,147
She likes it here.

537
00:23:03,148 --> 00:23:05,016
It's a damn nuisance, but what
am I gonna do, throw her out?

538
00:23:05,017 --> 00:23:06,150
Doesn't she have to go home?

539
00:23:06,151 --> 00:23:07,853
It's August.
Won't schools soon open?

540
00:23:07,854 --> 00:23:09,653
In Georgia? You never know.

541
00:23:09,654 --> 00:23:11,956
Come on. What is
this nonsense about quitting?

542
00:23:11,957 --> 00:23:14,826
I have had offers for many jobs.
After all, I'm bilingual.

543
00:23:14,827 --> 00:23:15,826
don't I know it.

544
00:23:15,827 --> 00:23:17,429
Remember that Russian
Trade Commission?

545
00:23:17,430 --> 00:23:18,930
They keep calling me
all the time.

546
00:23:18,931 --> 00:23:20,131
They want me very badly.

547
00:23:20,132 --> 00:23:22,032
I'll bet,
those Siberian wolves.

548
00:23:22,033 --> 00:23:24,236
So you better
find yourself another girl.

549
00:23:24,237 --> 00:23:25,498
All right!

550
00:23:27,005 --> 00:23:28,495
Dictation.

551
00:23:31,576 --> 00:23:34,346
Classified ad to run
in all Berlin papers.

552
00:23:34,347 --> 00:23:35,346
Quote...

553
00:23:35,347 --> 00:23:37,399
"Attractive
middle-aged executive...

554
00:23:37,400 --> 00:23:39,693
"wants attractive,
young secretary.

555
00:23:39,694 --> 00:23:41,986
"Must be versatile
and cooperative.

556
00:23:41,987 --> 00:23:45,223
"Excellent salary,
congenial working conditions...

557
00:23:45,224 --> 00:23:47,358
"fringe benefits."

558
00:23:47,359 --> 00:23:50,628
Fringe benefits? What is that?

559
00:23:50,629 --> 00:23:53,564
Little extras.
For instance, this morning...

560
00:23:53,565 --> 00:23:55,617
I was passing that fancy shop
on the Kurfuerstendamm...

561
00:23:55,618 --> 00:23:57,669
and there was this white
silk dress in the window...

562
00:23:57,670 --> 00:23:59,805
with polka dots all over it
and a matching hat.

563
00:23:59,806 --> 00:24:01,873
And a bag?
And matching shoes?

564
00:24:01,874 --> 00:24:03,741
Why not?

565
00:24:03,742 --> 00:24:04,743
I'll take the job.

566
00:24:04,744 --> 00:24:05,978
You got it.

567
00:24:05,979 --> 00:24:07,211
Danke schön.

568
00:24:07,212 --> 00:24:08,474
You're welcome schön.

569
00:24:11,783 --> 00:24:14,013
Please. Not while
you're chewing gum.

570
00:24:18,256 --> 00:24:19,891
That'll be all,
Fräulein Ingeborg.

571
00:24:19,892 --> 00:24:21,960
- More later.
- Anytime.

572
00:24:21,961 --> 00:24:23,127
Yes, Schlemmer?

573
00:24:23,128 --> 00:24:25,263
I called the garage.
I called his wife.

574
00:24:25,264 --> 00:24:26,430
No Fritz.

575
00:24:26,431 --> 00:24:27,799
I can see this is going
to be one of those days.

576
00:24:27,800 --> 00:24:28,900
You better call the police.

577
00:24:28,901 --> 00:24:29,900
I already did.

578
00:24:29,901 --> 00:24:31,503
Gave them a complete description
of the car...

579
00:24:31,504 --> 00:24:33,772
model, license number,
engine number.

580
00:24:33,773 --> 00:24:34,806
You're a good man, Schlemmer.

581
00:24:34,807 --> 00:24:35,806
Thank you, sir.

582
00:24:35,807 --> 00:24:36,808
Schlemmer, how much
are we paying you?

583
00:24:36,809 --> 00:24:37,808
Two hundred marks a week.

584
00:24:37,809 --> 00:24:39,544
Let's see. That would be
about fifty dollars.

585
00:24:39,545 --> 00:24:40,879
- That's all.
- That's enough.

586
00:24:40,880 --> 00:24:41,868
Yes, sir.

587
00:24:44,015 --> 00:24:46,317
Hello? Hello? Yes?

588
00:24:46,318 --> 00:24:48,686
Atlanta, Georgia?
Put it through.

589
00:24:48,687 --> 00:24:50,789
MacNamara, what's going on
there in Berlin?

590
00:24:50,790 --> 00:24:52,490
I have a letter here
from Scarlett.

591
00:24:52,491 --> 00:24:55,927
It says she's been going
to operas, concerts, museums.

592
00:24:55,928 --> 00:24:57,928
That doesn't sound
like my little girl.

593
00:24:57,929 --> 00:24:59,965
You're going to be
surprised, Mr. Hazeltine.

594
00:24:59,966 --> 00:25:01,417
She's a different person now.

595
00:25:01,418 --> 00:25:02,867
I don't mind telling you.

596
00:25:02,868 --> 00:25:04,503
We were a little worried
when she first arrived...

597
00:25:04,504 --> 00:25:06,037
but she turned out just fine.

598
00:25:06,038 --> 00:25:08,372
Well, I'll be damned!

599
00:25:08,373 --> 00:25:09,773
Anyway, you'll be
relieved to know...

600
00:25:09,774 --> 00:25:12,344
that Mrs. Hazeltine and I
are leaving for Europe today...

601
00:25:12,345 --> 00:25:14,513
and we're going to take
Scarlett off your hands.

602
00:25:14,514 --> 00:25:16,165
We'll be sorry to lose her.

603
00:25:16,166 --> 00:25:17,815
No, it was no bother at all.

604
00:25:17,816 --> 00:25:20,085
Two weeks, two months.
What's the difference?

605
00:25:20,086 --> 00:25:21,218
Well, I want you to know...

606
00:25:21,219 --> 00:25:23,104
that we're mighty grateful
to you, MacNamara.

607
00:25:23,105 --> 00:25:24,990
Actually, the reason
I'm making this trip...

608
00:25:24,991 --> 00:25:26,991
there's gonna be
a shift in personnel.

609
00:25:26,992 --> 00:25:29,294
We're naming a new head
of European operations...

610
00:25:29,295 --> 00:25:31,730
and you won't be forgotten, Mac.

611
00:25:31,731 --> 00:25:33,531
The London job?

612
00:25:33,532 --> 00:25:36,200
Well, I don't know what to say.

613
00:25:36,201 --> 00:25:38,502
I never expected
anything like that.

614
00:25:38,503 --> 00:25:41,172
Just to be considered
for the job is a great honor.

615
00:25:41,173 --> 00:25:42,207
Of course, I have been
with the company...

616
00:25:42,208 --> 00:25:43,607
for the past fifteen years...

617
00:25:43,608 --> 00:25:46,144
and I know the European market
like the inside of my pocket...

618
00:25:46,145 --> 00:25:47,145
It's your wife
on the other phone.

619
00:25:47,146 --> 00:25:48,178
She must talk to you.

620
00:25:48,179 --> 00:25:49,497
Not now.
I'm on long distance.

621
00:25:49,498 --> 00:25:50,814
I told her that,
but she insists.

622
00:25:50,815 --> 00:25:52,283
Would you hold on a minute,
Mr. Hazeltine?

623
00:25:52,284 --> 00:25:55,014
There's a little emergency
in the accounting department.

624
00:25:56,121 --> 00:25:58,055
What is it, Phyllis?
What's so important?

625
00:25:58,056 --> 00:26:00,525
Well, if you put it that way,
nothing, really.

626
00:26:00,526 --> 00:26:01,825
I just thought
you might be interested...

627
00:26:01,826 --> 00:26:04,462
in what's going on
around the house, mein führer.

628
00:26:04,463 --> 00:26:05,729
You out of your mind?

629
00:26:05,730 --> 00:26:08,066
I'm talking to Mr. Hazeltine
about the London job...

630
00:26:08,067 --> 00:26:09,466
and you want to chitchat?

631
00:26:09,467 --> 00:26:13,171
I'm sorry. It's just that
Miss Hazeltine is missing...

632
00:26:13,172 --> 00:26:14,873
but we can discuss it
some other time.

633
00:26:14,874 --> 00:26:16,840
- Bye.
- Bye.

634
00:26:16,841 --> 00:26:18,877
Missing?!
Wait a minute, Phyllis.

635
00:26:18,878 --> 00:26:19,977
Phyllis!

636
00:26:19,978 --> 00:26:21,312
What do you mean she's missing?

637
00:26:21,313 --> 00:26:23,882
Bertha took her breakfast up,
and she's not there.

638
00:26:23,883 --> 00:26:25,517
Her bed hasn't been slept in.

639
00:26:25,518 --> 00:26:26,584
Well, that's ridiculous.

640
00:26:26,585 --> 00:26:27,819
We got back from the movie
around 11:00...

641
00:26:27,820 --> 00:26:29,237
and Scarlett
went right upstairs.

642
00:26:29,238 --> 00:26:31,148
What could have happened to her?

643
00:26:31,149 --> 00:26:33,058
Who knows? Gone with the wind.

644
00:26:33,059 --> 00:26:34,224
Maybe she ran away.

645
00:26:34,225 --> 00:26:36,661
Maybe she was kidnapped
by a white slave ring.

646
00:26:36,662 --> 00:26:38,229
Oh, swell.
Hold on, will you?

647
00:26:38,230 --> 00:26:39,296
Trouble?

648
00:26:39,297 --> 00:26:41,499
I wish I were in hell
with my back broken.

649
00:26:41,500 --> 00:26:42,633
Sorry, Mr. Hazeltine.

650
00:26:42,634 --> 00:26:44,970
They come running to me
with all their little problems.

651
00:26:44,971 --> 00:26:47,339
About your trip.
What boat are you sailing on?

652
00:26:47,340 --> 00:26:49,240
Boat? Who's got time for that?

653
00:26:49,241 --> 00:26:50,441
Mrs. Hazeltine and I...

654
00:26:50,442 --> 00:26:52,243
are flying to New York
this afternoon...

655
00:26:52,244 --> 00:26:53,944
taking the overnight jet
to London.

656
00:26:53,945 --> 00:26:55,880
There's a connecting
flight to Berlin...

657
00:26:55,881 --> 00:26:57,983
and we'll be there
at noon tomorrow.

658
00:26:57,984 --> 00:27:00,084
Noon tomorrow?
You mean our time?

659
00:27:00,085 --> 00:27:02,954
Of course I'll tell Scarlett,
first chance I get.

660
00:27:02,955 --> 00:27:03,954
Yes, sir.

661
00:27:03,955 --> 00:27:06,024
We'll see you at the airport
unless those damn Commies...

662
00:27:06,025 --> 00:27:07,576
shoot the plane down.

663
00:27:07,577 --> 00:27:09,126
Yeah. Auf Wiedersehen.

664
00:27:09,127 --> 00:27:11,429
For God's sake, Phyllis,
we've got to find that idiot.

665
00:27:11,430 --> 00:27:12,998
Her parents are arriving
tomorrow.

666
00:27:12,999 --> 00:27:14,295
Where could she be?

667
00:27:14,833 --> 00:27:17,427
She doesn't know anybody
in Berlin except us.

668
00:27:18,436 --> 00:27:19,704
Well, have Bertha look again.

669
00:27:19,705 --> 00:27:21,489
Maybe she left a note.

670
00:27:21,490 --> 00:27:23,273
What about her luggage?

671
00:27:23,274 --> 00:27:25,377
I'm glad to hear
something is still there.

672
00:27:25,378 --> 00:27:27,478
No, I'm not blaming you.

673
00:27:27,479 --> 00:27:29,514
It's just that lousy
MacNamara luck.

674
00:27:29,515 --> 00:27:31,160
First I lost a bottling plant...

675
00:27:31,161 --> 00:27:32,806
and now I lose
the boss' daughter!

676
00:27:36,988 --> 00:27:38,223
I think
we are getting someplace.

677
00:27:38,224 --> 00:27:40,224
We found Fritz.

678
00:27:40,225 --> 00:27:42,292
Fritz? To hell with Fritz!

679
00:27:42,293 --> 00:27:44,460
It's the girl
we're looking for now.

680
00:27:44,461 --> 00:27:46,627
Precisely.
He has some information.

681
00:27:49,034 --> 00:27:50,200
Where is she?

682
00:27:50,201 --> 00:27:52,736
I do not know, not precisely...

683
00:27:52,737 --> 00:27:54,873
but last night, I dropped her
at the Brandenburg Gate.

684
00:27:54,874 --> 00:27:56,040
Brandenburg Gate? Why?

685
00:27:56,041 --> 00:27:57,608
That is where
I drop her every night...

686
00:27:57,609 --> 00:27:59,244
and that is where I pick
her up every morning.

687
00:27:59,245 --> 00:28:01,246
How long has this been going on?

688
00:28:01,247 --> 00:28:02,746
Since last month, sir.

689
00:28:02,747 --> 00:28:04,048
Usually, I get her
back to the house...

690
00:28:04,049 --> 00:28:05,350
before you wake up,
but this morning...

691
00:28:05,351 --> 00:28:06,684
I wait for her, and I wait.

692
00:28:06,685 --> 00:28:08,586
You mean, you've been helping
her sneak out behind my back?

693
00:28:08,587 --> 00:28:10,555
Yes, sir, but I have
a very good excuse.

694
00:28:10,556 --> 00:28:11,555
What?

695
00:28:11,556 --> 00:28:12,656
She pays me
a hundred marks a night...

696
00:28:12,657 --> 00:28:14,559
fifty for driving her,
fifty for not telling you.

697
00:28:14,560 --> 00:28:15,760
Do I have your permission
to fire him?

698
00:28:15,761 --> 00:28:17,094
Not yet!

699
00:28:17,095 --> 00:28:19,430
Now, let's go step by step.

700
00:28:19,431 --> 00:28:21,266
After you drop her
at the Brandenburg Gate...

701
00:28:21,267 --> 00:28:22,499
what does she do?

702
00:28:22,500 --> 00:28:25,370
She crosses the border
into East Berlin.

703
00:28:25,371 --> 00:28:26,437
East Berlin?

704
00:28:26,438 --> 00:28:27,571
That is why I am so worried...

705
00:28:27,572 --> 00:28:29,507
because this morning,
she did not come back.

706
00:28:29,508 --> 00:28:30,908
You're worried?

707
00:28:30,909 --> 00:28:33,605
I'm going down in flames,
and he's worried.

708
00:28:35,280 --> 00:28:37,098
Ingeborg, clear the switchboard.

709
00:28:37,099 --> 00:28:38,916
I want
Brigadier General Hartel...

710
00:28:38,917 --> 00:28:40,552
Commanding Officer
of the American sector.

711
00:28:40,553 --> 00:28:42,619
Next, get me Mayor Willy Brandt.

712
00:28:42,620 --> 00:28:43,655
Next, get me
the Police Commissioner...

713
00:28:43,656 --> 00:28:44,888
of West Berlin.

714
00:28:44,889 --> 00:28:47,425
Next, I want to speak
to the U.S. Ambassador in Bonn.

715
00:28:47,426 --> 00:28:48,949
You got that? OK.

716
00:28:50,161 --> 00:28:52,280
Fritz, you wait downstairs.
I may need you later.

717
00:28:52,281 --> 00:28:54,399
Schlemmer, how can we find out
what happened to her?

718
00:28:54,400 --> 00:28:56,284
Can we get any information
from East Berlin?

719
00:28:56,285 --> 00:28:58,169
Only through official channels
in triplicate.

720
00:28:58,170 --> 00:28:59,204
What if we just
picked up the phone...

721
00:28:59,205 --> 00:29:00,238
and called the authorities
over there?

722
00:29:00,239 --> 00:29:02,272
- It is not that easy.
- Why not?

723
00:29:02,273 --> 00:29:04,342
There's no direct phone service
to East Berlin.

724
00:29:04,343 --> 00:29:05,342
You have to call Stockholm.

725
00:29:05,343 --> 00:29:06,861
From there it goes
through Warsaw...

726
00:29:06,862 --> 00:29:08,378
to Leipzig,
then to East Berlin.

727
00:29:08,379 --> 00:29:10,415
Nine times out of ten,
you get the wrong number.

728
00:29:10,416 --> 00:29:12,144
- Try it anyway.
- Yes, sir.

729
00:29:17,255 --> 00:29:18,244
Schnellmachen!

730
00:29:21,626 --> 00:29:23,193
Yes?

731
00:29:23,194 --> 00:29:25,363
General Hartel
is out on army maneuvers?

732
00:29:25,364 --> 00:29:27,532
Well, what about
Mayor Willy Brandt?

733
00:29:27,533 --> 00:29:28,950
He's watching the maneuvers.

734
00:29:28,951 --> 00:29:30,367
And the Police Commissioner?

735
00:29:30,368 --> 00:29:31,770
I see.
He's watching Willy Brandt.

736
00:29:31,771 --> 00:29:33,739
So who's minding the store?

737
00:29:33,740 --> 00:29:35,706
What about the call to Bonn?

738
00:29:35,707 --> 00:29:38,376
Our ambassador is back
in Washington for consulation?

739
00:29:38,377 --> 00:29:39,861
Come in, come in.
I'll be right with you.

740
00:29:39,862 --> 00:29:41,346
Get me Washington,
the State Department...

741
00:29:41,347 --> 00:29:42,579
whoever answers...

742
00:29:42,580 --> 00:29:44,716
Dean Rusk, Dean Acheson,
Dean anybody.

743
00:29:44,717 --> 00:29:46,151
And if you have no luck there...

744
00:29:46,152 --> 00:29:47,584
get me Senator Talmadge
of Georgia.

745
00:29:47,585 --> 00:29:50,850
If he isn't in,
try Huntley and Brinkley at NBC.

746
00:29:51,723 --> 00:29:52,990
Scarlett!

747
00:29:52,991 --> 00:29:54,893
What's all the excitement?

748
00:29:54,894 --> 00:29:57,161
Oh, nothing.

749
00:29:57,162 --> 00:29:58,696
You just scared
the hell out of us!

750
00:29:58,697 --> 00:30:00,131
You all right?

751
00:30:00,132 --> 00:30:01,565
I'm just marvy.

752
00:30:01,566 --> 00:30:02,934
What were you doing
in East Berlin?

753
00:30:02,935 --> 00:30:04,653
You mean, last night?

754
00:30:04,654 --> 00:30:06,370
I mean all those nights.

755
00:30:06,371 --> 00:30:08,740
There's this boy
over there.

756
00:30:08,741 --> 00:30:10,073
Wow!

757
00:30:10,074 --> 00:30:11,709
What boy?
What have you been up to?

758
00:30:11,710 --> 00:30:14,111
I met him
about six weeks ago.

759
00:30:14,112 --> 00:30:16,614
I went into East Berlin,
and there was this parade...

760
00:30:16,615 --> 00:30:18,349
and they wanted to arrest me.

761
00:30:18,350 --> 00:30:19,883
Arrest you?

762
00:30:19,884 --> 00:30:21,752
Because I was taking pictures.

763
00:30:21,753 --> 00:30:24,621
And then this boy-
he was in the parade...

764
00:30:24,622 --> 00:30:26,690
he said to the policemen
I shouldn't be arrested.

765
00:30:26,691 --> 00:30:30,829
I should be pitied because I was
a typical bourgeois parasite...

766
00:30:30,830 --> 00:30:34,866
and the rotten fruit
of a corrupt civilization.

767
00:30:34,867 --> 00:30:37,402
So naturally,
